{"title_page": "Nevin Birsa (Slovene poet)", "text_new": "{{short description|Slovene poet}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n'''Nevin Birsa''' (August 25, 1947 \u2013 October 1, 2003) was a [[Slovene language|Slovene]] [[poet]].\n\nBirsa was born in the village of [[Branik]] (then known as Rihemberk) in the [[Vipava Valley]], in western [[Slovenia]]. He studied at the Pedagogic Academy of the [[University of Ljubljana]]. He published numerous poetry collections, which gained widespread recognition, especially after his talent was pointed out by the poet and author [[Ciril Zlobec]]. Birsa lived in his home village most of his life, leading a simple lifestyle. His highly sophisticated poetry, which showed the influence of [[Georg Trakl]], [[Rainer Maria Rilke]], and [[Edvard Kocbek]], attracted considerable interest regarding his personality.\n\nBirsa was a quite prolific author. During his lifetime, he published 16 poetry collection and a posthumous collection of his unedited poetry was published in 2004.\n\nBirsa died in his home village in 2003 and is buried at the local cemetery. In 2006, the local authorities created memorial spot in the local library.<ref>http://www.branik.si/krajevna-knjiznica-branik</ref> His birthplace is nearby.\n\n== Volumes of poetry ==\n*Elektronke v o\u010de, 1970\n*Rihemberk, 1974\n*Jelen cvete med debli, 1975\n*Pesni\u0161ki list, 1977\n*Nove ljubezenske pesmi, 1979\n*Poskus maga, 1987\n*Kdo ima \u017eare\u010di klju\u010d, 1990\n*Prva svetloba, 1992\n*Samotni napis mavrice, 1994\n*Skat \u0161irokega jutra, 1996\n*Kresnice in pesnik (izbor iz prej\u0161njih zbirk), 1997\n*\u017divali in ro\u017ee, 1999\n*Skice krvi in zvezd, 2001\n*Boj za rde\u010de ble\u0161\u010danje, 2001\n*Modrijan ali klovn, 2003\n*To pomlad sem od\u0161el v neznano (Collected works), 2004\n\n== Literature ==\n*Andrej Lutman, \"Postaja na brezpotju, Spis o pesnjenju Nevina Birse\", ''Mentor'' 25, no. 1\u20132 (2004).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*Bojan Bratina, \"Nevin Birsa\" in ''Kronika Rihemberka - Branika II'' (Nova Gorica: KS Branik, 2006)\n*Eva Lu\u0161ina, \"Nevin Birsa\" in Nevin Birsa, ''Skice krvi in zvezd'' (Nova Gorica: Zalo\u017eba Branko, 2001)\n*[[Matija Ogrin]], \"Nevin Birsa: Prva svetloba\" in ''Literatura'', yr. 4,n. 17 (1992), 91\n*[[Josip Osti]], \"Pesni\u0161ka ozemlja in ozvezdja. Nevin Birsa: Skice krvi in zvezd\" in ''[[Sodobnost]]'', yr. 65, n. 20 (October 2001)\n*Radivoj Pahor, \"Nevinu\" in ''Primorska sre\u010danja'', n. 269/270 (2003), 78\n\n{{Nova Gorica |state=collapsed}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birsa, Nevin}}\n[[Category:Slovenian poets]]\n[[Category:People from the City Municipality of Nova Gorica]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Ljubljana alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n\n\n{{slovenia-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Slovene poet}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2013}}\n'''Nevin Birsa''' (August 25, 1947 \u2013 October 1, 2003) was a [[Slovene language|Slovene]] [[poet]].\n\nBirsa was born in the village of [[Branik]] (then known as Rihemberk) in the [[Vipava Valley]], in western [[Slovenia]]. He studied at the Pedagogic Academy of the [[University of Ljubljana]]. He published numerous poetry collections, which gained widespread recognition, especially after his talent was pointed out by the poet and author [[Ciril Zlobec]]. Birsa lived in his home village most of his life, leading a simple lifestyle. His highly sophisticated poetry, which showed the influence of [[Georg Trakl]], [[Rainer Maria Rilke]], and [[Edvard Kocbek]], attracted considerable interest regarding his personality.\n\nBirsa was a quite prolific author. During his lifetime, he published 16 poetry collection and a posthumous collection of his unedited poetry was published in 2004.\n\nBirsa died in his home village in 2003 and is buried at the local cemetery. In 2006, the local authorities created memorial spot in the local library.<ref>http://www.branik.si/krajevna-knjiznica-branik</ref> His birthplace is nearby.\n\n== Volumes of poetry ==\n*Elektronke v o\u010de, 1970\n*Rihemberk, 1974\n*Jelen cvete med debli, 1975\n*Pesni\u0161ki list, 1977\n*Nove ljubezenske pesmi, 1979\n*Poskus maga, 1987\n*Kdo ima \u017eare\u010di klju\u010d, 1990\n*Prva svetloba, 1992\n*Samotni napis mavrice, 1994\n*Skat \u0161irokega jutra, 1996\n*Kresnice in pesnik (izbor iz prej\u0161njih zbirk), 1997\n*\u017divali in ro\u017ee, 1999\n*Skice krvi in zvezd, 2001\n*Boj za rde\u010de ble\u0161\u010danje, 2001\n*Modrijan ali klovn, 2003\n*To pomlad sem od\u0161el v neznano (Collected works), 2004\n\n== Literature ==\n*Andrej Lutman, \"Postaja na brezpotju, Spis o pesnjenju Nevina Birse\", ''Mentor'' 25, no. 1\u20132 (2004).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*Bojan Bratina, \"Nevin Birsa\" in ''Kronika Rihemberka - Branika II'' (Nova Gorica: KS Branik, 2006)\n*Eva Lu\u0161ina, \"Nevin Birsa\" in Nevin Birsa, ''Skice krvi in zvezd'' (Nova Gorica: Zalo\u017eba Branko, 2001)\n*[[Matija Ogrin]], \"Nevin Birsa: Prva svetloba\" in ''Literatura'', yr. 4,n. 17 (1992), 91\n*[[Josip Osti]], \"Pesni\u0161ka ozemlja in ozvezdja. Nevin Birsa: Skice krvi in zvezd\" in ''[[Sodobnost]]'', yr. 65, n. 20 (October 2001)\n*Radivoj Pahor, \"Nevinu\" in ''Primorska sre\u010danja'', n. 269/270 (2003), 78\n\n{{Nova Gorica |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birsa, Nevin}}\n[[Category:Slovenian poets]]\n[[Category:People from the City Municipality of Nova Gorica]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Ljubljana alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n\n\n{{slovenia-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nevin_Birsa_(Slovene_poet)"}
{"title_page": "Ladies in Black (film)", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ladies in Black\n| image          = File:LadiesInBlackOfficialPoster.jpeg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Bruce Beresford]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sue Milliken]]\n* [[Allanah Zitserman]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Bruce Beresford\n* Sue Milliken\n}}\n| based on       = ''The Women in Black''<br> by [[Madeleine St John]]\n| starring       ={{Plainlist|\n* [[Angourie Rice]]\n* [[Rachael Taylor]]\n* [[Julia Ormond]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Christopher Gordon (composer)|Christopher Gordon]]\n| cinematography = [[Peter James (cinematographer)|Peter James]]\n| editing        = [[Mark Warner (film editor)|Mark Warner]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Lumila Films Pty Ltd\n* The Ruskin Company\n* Ladies in Black SPV Pty Ltd\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures]]\n| released       = 20 September 2018\n| runtime        = 109 minutes\n| country        = [[Australia]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $11 million<ref name=\"Financial Review\">{{cite news |last1= Carruthers |first1=Fiona | title=Why Ladies in Black became the year's surprise hit | date=21 December 2018 | work=Australian Financial Review | url=https://www.afr.com/lifestyle/arts-and-entertainment/why-ladies-in-black-became-the-years-surprise-hit-20181220-h19bbj |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = $9,326,154<ref name=\"TheNumbers\">{{cite web|title=Ladies in Black | url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Ladies-in-Black-(Australia) | website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | publisher= Nash Information Services |date=2018 | accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Ladies in Black''''' is a 2018 Australian [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Bruce Beresford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ladiesinblackmovie.com.au/#|title=Ladies in Black Movie {{!}} In Cinemas 20 September|website=www.ladiesinblackmovie.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903115634/https://www.ladiesinblackmovie.com.au/|archive-date=3 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Starring [[Angourie Rice]], [[Rachael Taylor]], [[Julia Ormond]], [[Ryan Corr]] and [[Shane Jacobson]], the film is based on the 1993 novel ''[[The Women in Black]]'' by [[Madeleine St John]], and tells the story of a group of department store employees in 1959 Sydney. The film was released on 20 September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/ladies-in-black-2018/35635/|title=Ladies in Black (2018) - The Screen Guide - Screen Australia|website=www.screenaustralia.gov.au|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nLisa is hired as a new assistant at Goode's department store in Sydney during the 1959 Christmas season. She makes friends with Fay, who is initially wary of immigrants, Patty, who seeks more attention from her husband, and Magda, an immigrant from Slovenia who introduces her to her other European friends. Patty buys a pink nightdress that gets her the attention from her husband that she seeks, but he believes that he has upset her with his attention and disappears for the season. Magda invites Lisa and Fay to a New Year's Eve party at Magda's house and introduces Fay to Rudi, a Hungarian immigrant who is looking for a wife. Lisa is introduced to Michael, the son of Hungarian immigrants to Australia. A dress Lisa wants to buy is marked down from 150 guineas to 75 guineas during the next summer sale, then later to 50 guineas. Patty's husband returns and they reconcile when she explains that she wants his attention, and Patty soon becomes pregnant. Lisa gets honours on her school leaving exam and applies for a scholarship at Sydney University after getting the approval of her father. Rudi buys a new apartment and proposes to Fay in it. Lisa is upset that the dress she likes is no longer on display, but Magda has only hidden it away now that it has been reduced to 35 guineas, which Lisa can now afford. She buys the dress and wears it to a party celebrating her test scores. Magda says that she has picked out a location for a store where she will sell high-end fashion. Magda asks Lisa what she will do after finishing her studies at Sydney University and Lisa says that she wants to be an actress, or a poet, or a novelist, or maybe all three.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!--- Cast and order per tombstone closing credits, roles per closing credits scroll --->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Julia Ormond]] as Magda\n* [[Angourie Rice]] as Lisa\n* [[Rachael Taylor]] as Fay\n* [[Ryan Corr]] as Rudi\n* [[Susie Porter]] as Mrs. Miles\n* [[Shane Jacobson]] as Mr. Miles\n* [[Noni Hazlehurst]] as Miss Cartwright\n* [[Nicholas Hammond]] as Mr. Ryder\n* Alison McGirr as Patty\n* [[Vincent Perez]] as Stefan\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n''Ladies in Black'' was twenty years in the making, with writer-director [[Bruce Beresford]] attached to the project. Beresford and novelist [[Madeleine St John]], who wrote the book of which the film is an adaptation, were university friends, and Beresford had promised to one day adapt her novel into film since first reading it around its original publication.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/sep/09/bruce-beresford-at-last-making-the-film-that-obsessed-me-for-30-years Bruce Beresford: At last, making the film that obsessed me for 30 years]</ref> In October 2017, the cast was announced, with principal production commencing that month in [[Sydney, Australia|Sydney]], Australia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/angourie-rice-star-australian-period-drama-ladies-black-1045118|title=Angourie Rice to Star in Australian Period Drama 'Ladies in Black'|last=Bulbeck|first=Pip|date=3 October 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-10-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/sa/media-centre/news/2017/10-04-ladies-in-black-cast-announced|title=An Australian and International ensemble cast join Bruce Beresford's Ladies in Black {{!}} Media centre \u2013 Screen Australia|website=Screen Australia|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Box office===\nPrior to release, ''Ladies in Black'' was projected to have \"a sizable opening weekend and a long run sustained by word-of-mouth and repeat business.\"<ref>[https://www.if.com.au/bruce-beresfords-ladies-in-black-is-dressed-for-success/ Bruce Beresford\u2019s \u2018Ladies in Black\u2019 is dressed for success]</ref> On its opening weekend, the film earned $1,865,134 in Australia, placing second behind ''[[Johnny English Strikes Again]]''.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fLADIESINBLACK01&country=AU&wk=2018W41&id=_fLADIESINBLACK01&p=.htm | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |title=Ladies in Black}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Ladies in Black'' received generally positive reviews from critics. On [[Review aggregator|review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 85% based on 27 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.96/10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ladies_in_black|title=Ladies in Black (2018)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nNeil Young of the ''[[The Hollywood Reporter|Hollywood Reporter]]'' said of the film, \"''Ladies in Black'' quietly but effectively points out the seldom-stressed positives of immigration and integration, and thus deserves attention far beyond its own native shores\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/ladies-black-1142951|title='Ladies in Black': Film Review|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> Jake Wilson in ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' says the period details \"carry the authority of first-hand experience\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/ladies-in-black-review-counter-culture-explored-20180919-h15kxu.html|title=Ladies in Black review: Counter culture explored|last=Wilson|first=Jake|date=19 September 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=7 October 2018}}</ref> Australian film critic [[David Stratton]], writing for ''[[The Australian]]'', wrote \"''Ladies in Black'' may be seen mistakenly as lightweight or slight; it isn't. It brims with subtext and nuance and at the same time succeeds in being a thoroughly enjoyable entertainment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/david-stratton-on-ladies-in-black-beast/news-story/12d72f0bba70fe2a873771bf9978d0ec |title=David Stratton on Ladies in Black |work=The Australian |url-access=subscription |language=en|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=15|[[AACTA Awards]]<br><small>([[8th AACTA Awards|8th]])</small>\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|[[Sue Milliken]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Allanah Zitserman]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Bruce Beresford]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Sue Milliken\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress]]\n|[[Julia Ormond]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Angourie Rice]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|[[Noni Hazlehurst]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n|[[Peter James (cinematographer)|Peter James]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n|[[Mark Warner (film editor)|Mark Warner]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Original Music Score|Best Original Music Score]]\n|[[Christopher Gordon (composer)|Christopher Gordon]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n|Wendy Cork\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[AACTA Award for Best Hair and Makeup|Best Hair and Makeup]]\n|Anna Gray\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Beth Halsted\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Jen Lamphee\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|6684884}}\n\n{{Bruce Beresford}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Australian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Australian historical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bruce Beresford]]\n[[Category:Films set in department stores]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1960]]\n[[Category:Films based on Australian novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ladies in Black\n| image          = File:LadiesInBlackOfficialPoster.jpeg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Bruce Beresford]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sue Milliken]]\n* [[Allanah Zitserman]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Bruce Beresford\n* Sue Milliken\n}}\n| based on       = ''The Women in Black''<br> by [[Madeleine St John]]\n| starring       ={{Plainlist|\n* [[Angourie Rice]]\n* [[Rachael Taylor]]\n* [[Julia Ormond]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Christopher Gordon (composer)|Christopher Gordon]]\n| cinematography = [[Peter James (cinematographer)|Peter James]]\n| editing        = [[Mark Warner (film editor)|Mark Warner]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Lumila Films Pty Ltd\n* The Ruskin Company\n* Ladies in Black SPV Pty Ltd\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures]]\n| released       = 20 September 2018\n| runtime        = 109 minutes\n| country        = [[Australia]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $11 million<ref name=\"Financial Review\">{{cite news |last1= Carruthers |first1=Fiona | title=Why Ladies in Black became the year's surprise hit | date=21 December 2018 | work=Australian Financial Review | url=https://www.afr.com/lifestyle/arts-and-entertainment/why-ladies-in-black-became-the-years-surprise-hit-20181220-h19bbj |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = $9,326,154<ref name=\"TheNumbers\">{{cite web|title=Ladies in Black | url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Ladies-in-Black-(Australia) | website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | publisher= Nash Information Services |date=2018 | accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Ladies in Black''''' is a 2018 Australian [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Bruce Beresford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ladiesinblackmovie.com.au/#|title=Ladies in Black Movie {{!}} In Cinemas 20 September|website=www.ladiesinblackmovie.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903115634/https://www.ladiesinblackmovie.com.au/|archive-date=3 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Starring [[Angourie Rice]], [[Rachael Taylor]], [[Julia Ormond]], [[Ryan Corr]] and [[Shane Jacobson]], the film is based on the 1993 novel ''[[The Women in Black]]'' by [[Madeleine St John]], and tells the story of a group of department store employees in 1959 Sydney. The film was released on 20 September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/ladies-in-black-2018/35635/|title=Ladies in Black (2018) - The Screen Guide - Screen Australia|website=www.screenaustralia.gov.au|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nLisa is hired as a new assistant at Goode's department store in Sydney during the 1959 Christmas season. She makes friends with Fay, who is initially wary of immigrants, Patty, who seeks more attention from her husband, and Magda, an immigrant from Slovenia who introduces her to her other European friends. Patty buys a pink nightdress that gets her the attention from her husband that she seeks, but he believes that he has upset her with his attention and disappears for the season. Magda invites Lisa and Fay to a New Year's Eve party at Magda's house and introduces Fay to Rudi, a Hungarian immigrant who is looking for a wife. Lisa is introduced to Michael, the son of Hungarian immigrants to Australia. A dress Lisa wants to buy is marked down from 150 guineas to 75 guineas during the next summer sale, then later to 50 guineas. Patty's husband returns and they reconcile when she explains that she wants his attention, and Patty soon becomes pregnant. Lisa gets honours on her school leaving exam and applies for a scholarship at Sydney University after getting the approval of her father. Rudi buys a new apartment and proposes to Fay in it. Lisa is upset that the dress she likes is no longer on display, but Magda has only hidden it away now that it has been reduced to 35 guineas, which Lisa can now afford. She buys the dress and wears it to a party celebrating her test scores. Magda says that she has picked out a location for a store where she will sell high-end fashion. Magda asks Lisa what she will do after finishing her studies at Sydney University and Lisa says that she wants to be an actress, or a poet, or a novelist, or maybe all three.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!--- Cast and order per tombstone closing credits, roles per closing credits scroll --->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Julia Ormond]] as Magda\n* [[Angourie Rice]] as Lisa\n* [[Rachael Taylor]] as Fay\n* [[Ryan Corr]] as Rudi\n* [[Susie Porter]] as Mrs. Miles\n* [[Shane Jacobson]] as Mr. Miles\n* [[Noni Hazlehurst]] as Miss Cartwright\n* [[Nicholas Hammond]] as Mr. Ryder\n* Alison McGirr as Patty\n* [[Vincent Perez]] as Stefan\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n''Ladies in Black'' was twenty years in the making, with writer-director [[Bruce Beresford]] attached to the project. Beresford and novelist [[Madeleine St John]], who wrote the book of which the film is an adaptation, were university friends, and Beresford had promised to one day adapt her novel into film since first reading it around its original publication.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/sep/09/bruce-beresford-at-last-making-the-film-that-obsessed-me-for-30-years Bruce Beresford: At last, making the film that obsessed me for 30 years]</ref> In October 2017, the cast was announced, with principal production commencing that month in [[Sydney, Australia|Sydney]], Australia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/angourie-rice-star-australian-period-drama-ladies-black-1045118|title=Angourie Rice to Star in Australian Period Drama 'Ladies in Black'|last=Bulbeck|first=Pip|date=3 October 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-10-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/sa/media-centre/news/2017/10-04-ladies-in-black-cast-announced|title=An Australian and International ensemble cast join Bruce Beresford's Ladies in Black {{!}} Media centre \u2013 Screen Australia|website=Screen Australia|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Box office===\nPrior to release, ''Ladies in Black'' was projected to have \"a sizable opening weekend and a long run sustained by word-of-mouth and repeat business.\"<ref>[https://www.if.com.au/bruce-beresfords-ladies-in-black-is-dressed-for-success/ Bruce Beresford\u2019s \u2018Ladies in Black\u2019 is dressed for success]</ref> On its opening weekend, the film earned $1,865,134 in Australia, placing second behind ''[[Johnny English Strikes Again]]''.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fLADIESINBLACK01&country=AU&wk=2018W41&id=_fLADIESINBLACK01&p=.htm | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |title=Ladies in Black}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Ladies in Black'' received generally positive reviews from critics. On [[Review aggregator|review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 85% based on 27 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.96/10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ladies_in_black|title=Ladies in Black (2018)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nNeil Young of the ''[[The Hollywood Reporter|Hollywood Reporter]]'' said of the film, \"''Ladies in Black'' quietly but effectively points out the seldom-stressed positives of immigration and integration, and thus deserves attention far beyond its own native shores\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/ladies-black-1142951|title='Ladies in Black': Film Review|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> Jake Wilson in ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' says the period details \"carry the authority of first-hand experience\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/ladies-in-black-review-counter-culture-explored-20180919-h15kxu.html|title=Ladies in Black review: Counter culture explored|last=Wilson|first=Jake|date=19 September 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=7 October 2018}}</ref> Australian film critic [[David Stratton]], writing for ''[[The Australian]]'', wrote \"''Ladies in Black'' may be seen mistakenly as lightweight or slight; it isn't. It brims with subtext and nuance and at the same time succeeds in being a thoroughly enjoyable entertainment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/david-stratton-on-ladies-in-black-beast/news-story/12d72f0bba70fe2a873771bf9978d0ec |title=David Stratton on Ladies in Black |work=The Australian |url-access=subscription |language=en|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=15|[[AACTA Awards]]<br><small>([[8th AACTA Awards|8th]])</small>\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|[[Sue Milliken]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Allanah Zitserman]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Bruce Beresford]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Sue Milliken\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress]]\n|[[Julia Ormond]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Angourie Rice]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|[[Noni Hazlehurst]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n|[[Peter James (cinematographer)|Peter James]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n|[[Mark Warner (film editor)|Mark Warner]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Original Music Score|Best Original Music Score]]\n|[[Christopher Gordon (composer)|Christopher Gordon]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n|Wendy Cork\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[AACTA Award for Best Hair and Makeup|Best Hair and Makeup]]\n|Anna Gray\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Beth Halsted\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Jen Lamphee\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|6684884}}\n\n{{Bruce Beresford}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Australian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Australian historical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bruce Beresford]]\n[[Category:Films set in department stores]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1960]]\n[[Category:Films based on Australian novels]]\n", "name_user": "Keith-264", "label": "safe", "comment": "EngvarB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ladies_in_Black_(film)"}
